"Tung Y.-T., Chen L.-J., Chen Y.-P., Lin S.-T.","In situ methane recovery and carbon dioxide sequestration in methane hydrates: A molecular dynamics simulation study",2011,"Journal of Physical Chemistry B","115","51",,"15295","15302",,,10.1021/jp2088675,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84255205002&partnerID=40&md5=40d90c959d484054680ec2922d537df7","Department of Chemical Engineering, National Taiwan University, Taipei 10617, Taiwan","Tung, Y.-T., Department of Chemical Engineering, National Taiwan University, Taipei 10617, Taiwan; Chen, L.-J., Department of Chemical Engineering, National Taiwan University, Taipei 10617, Taiwan; Chen, Y.-P., Department of Chemical Engineering, National Taiwan University, Taipei 10617, Taiwan; Lin, S.-T., Department of Chemical Engineering, National Taiwan University, Taipei 10617, Taiwan","One intriguing idea for the simultaneous recovery of energy and sequestration of global warming gas is proposed by the transformation of methane hydrates to carbon dioxide hydrates with the injection of liquid CO 2. Here we use molecular dynamics simulations to show that the replacement can take place without melting of the network of hydrogen-bonded water molecules. Depending on the distance to the interface between the liquid CO2 and solid clathrate hydrate, we find that the replacement occurs either via direct swapping of methane and CO2 or via a transient co-occupation of both methane and CO2 in one cavity. Our results suggest that, with a careful design of the operation condition, it is possible to replace methane from methane hydrates with CO2 in the solid phase without much change in the geological stability. © 2011 American Chemical Society.",,"Carbon dioxide; Computer simulation; Dynamics; Global warming; Hydration; Hydrogen; Liquids; Methane; Molecular dynamics; Phase interfaces; Carbon dioxide sequestration; Clathrate hydrate; Hydrogen-bonded water molecules; In-situ; Liquid CO; Methane hydrates; Methane recovery; Molecular dynamics simulations; Operation conditions; Solid-phase; Gas hydrates",,,,,,"Kvenvolden, K.A., (1993) Rev. Geophys., 31, p. 173; Gornitz, V., Fung, I., (1994) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 8, p. 335; Dickens, G.R., Paull, C.K., Wallace, P., (1997) Nature, 385, p. 426; Haq, B.U., (1999) Science, 285, p. 543; Lopez, C., Spence, G., Hyndman, R., Kelley, D., (2010) Geology, 38, p. 967; Sultan, N., Cochonat, P., Canals, M., Cattaneo, A., Dennielou, B., Haflidason, H., Laberg, J.S., Wilson, C., (2004) Marine Geol., 213, p. 291; Pearce, F., (2009) New Scientist, 202, p. 30; Ohgaki, K., Takano, K., Sangawa, H., Matsubara, T., Nakano, S., (1996) J. Chem. Eng. Jpn., 29, p. 478; Ohgaki, K., Takano, K., Moritoki, M., (1994) Kagaku Kogaku Ronbunshu, 20, p. 121; Lee, H., Seo, Y., Seo, Y.T., Moudrakovski, I.L., Ripmeester, J.A., (2003) Angew. Chem., Int. Ed., 42, p. 5048; Yoon, J.H., Kawamura, T., Yamamoto, Y., Komai, T., (2004) J. Phys. Chem. A, 108, p. 5057; Park, Y., Kim, D.Y., Lee, J.W., Huh, D.G., Park, K.P., Lee, J., Lee, H., (2006) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A., 103, p. 12690; Ota, M., Saito, T., Aida, T., Watanabe, M., Sato, Y., Smith, R.L., Inomata, H., (2007) AIChE J., 53, p. 2715; Tegze, G., Granasy, L., Kvamme, B., (2007) Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys., 9, p. 3104; Zhou, X.T., Fan, S.S., Liang, D.Q., Du, J.W., (2008) Energy Convers. Manage., 49, p. 2124; Jung, J.W., Espinoza, D.N., Santamarina, J.C., (2010) J. Geophys. Res.-Solid Earth, 115, p. 10102; Ota, M., Abe, Y., Watanabe, M., Smith, R.L., Inomata, H., (2005) Fluid Phase Equilib., 228, p. 553; Ota, M., Morohashi, K., Abe, Y., Watanabe, M., Smith, R.L., Inomata, H., (2005) Energy Convers. Manage., 46, p. 1680; Moon, C., Taylor, P.C., Rodger, P.M., (2003) J. Am. Chem. Soc., 125, p. 4706; Anderson, B.J., Tester, J.W., Borghi, G.P., Trout, B.L., (2005) J. Am. Chem. Soc., 127, p. 17852; Vatamanu, J., Kusalik, P.G., (2006) J. Am. Chem. Soc., 128, p. 15588; English, N.J., Phelan, G.M., (2009) J. Chem. Phys., 131, p. 074704;